column168: On March 2, a fiberboard package with no indication of hazardous material content was delivered from Thomas Scientific to its final destination at PNNL.  Upon opening, it was discovered there were two 500 microcurie each Po-210 static eliminators.  On March 3, further investigations determined that a second package containing twenty-two 500 microcurie Po-210 static eliminators was en route.  Both the original and the second package should be marked UN2911.  The second package should also have a shipping paper and be marked RQ.  On March 3, the second unopened package was stopped at an intermediate PNNL location (790 6th Street, Richland, WA), correctly prepared by a qualified PNNL shipper, and forwarded on to its final destination.  There was no damage to or release from either package.  Thomas Scientific was contacted to advise them of the error and to request corrected future shipping.
column169: Customer service at Thomas Scientific, who is a distributor, reported that their system indicated the material was not regulated.  Documentation from the manufacturer (NRD) indicates the materials are regulated.  PNNL has previously received unmarked Po-210 static eliminators but I don't know if the previous items were received from Thomas Scientific.  Thomas Scientific was advised of the error and requested to correct their system.    No other recommendations.

Approximately 5 gallons of battery acid released to the trailer floor and asphalt parking area below. The battery was not damaged due to the incident. column168: At 23:40 on 3/2/15 the conductor of the M-SHLC-02 detected a odor coming from the residue tank car AXLX 1730 (last contained Chlorine) while setting out in the Kansas City Southern (KCS) Leesville, LA yard.  KCS Environmental + Hazmat Department dispatched emergency response contractors to investigate.  Local emergency responders, the Louisiana State Police (LSP), and CHEMTREC were all notified.  Local fire department emergency responders arrived, assessed the area but did not locate an odor, and subsequently demobilized from the site. Upon arrival, LSP and the response contractor detected a slight chlorine odor emanating from AXLX 1730.  During investigation, the B End Liquid Valve was found to be in the open position, one and one quarter turn open and the secondary closure plug was loose. The valve was secured (closed) stopping the active leak and the plug was secured tool tight.  Additionally, as information, both vapor valve secondary closure plugs were found to be less than tool tight and both liquid valve secondary closure plugs were found to be less than tool tight. The protective housing lid was found in the closed and secured position, with shipper (un-loader consignee)  seal in tact.  Once secure, the response contractor decontaminated the protective housing and reassessed to ensure the leak had been stopped.     File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. Contact Shipper and consignee for scale weight availability.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.
column198: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY

column168: Car was found leaking from flange/gasket that connects bottom discharge valve to tank body in Laurel, Mt Yard roundhouse track near BNSF fuel unloading facility.  Car equipped with Top Operated Bottom Outlet valve.  Valve was found approx. 1 turn in the open position.  Further inspection of valve revealed that packing nut was found tight and bottomed out allowing for a loose condition of the valve operating rod.  Closing valve stopped flow of material leaking from above valve/flange.    Car was found leaking at a rate of approximately 25 gallons per minute.  Unknown as to how long valve had been in above condition. It did appear as if most loss occurred at the leak site.      Pans were placed under the leaking car to prevent additional ground contamination.  Once the valve was closed, the remaining fuel was pumped from the tank by Locomotive Service Inc.    Track was removed along with contaminated soil from the spill area.    Tank car owner was contacted(BNSF) and appraised of the condition of the car.  Owner assigned a Home Shop for repairs.
column169: Training of the loading(shippers) operators in the proper use/inspection of the Top Operating Bottom Outlet Valve.  The leaking valve was found without proper packing allowing for the operating rod to open during transportation causing material to bypass the valve seat into the discharge nozzle where it leaked.    Closer inspection of the discharge nozzle flange gasket for signs of leakage/misalignment during loading.

column168: Quick Fuel Fleet Services driver was fueling a train locomotive utilizing a guage signifying when the tank was full. Driver stopped fueling the train when the guage needle was located approximately between 3/4 to full. The guage was not calibrated correctly and the tank for the locomotive was overfilled which caused diesel fuel to discharge out a vent pipe located on the opposite side of the train where the fueling occurred. Approximately 20 galllons of diesel fuel was discharged on soil and ashphalt pavement.     Quick Fuel Fleet Services hired a subcontractor,SWS Environmental Services, to remove the diesel fuel that was located on the asphalt surface and remove all diesel fuel impacted soil from adjacent to the railroad tracks.
column169: Have railroad personnel recalibrate the guage to accurately reflect the contents of the locomotive fuel tank.

column168: Haz-Mat employee attempted to unload the Petroleum Crude Oil into a storage tank facility. During the unloading process the storage tank had reached it's capacity and began to over flow from the over flow line into the containment around the storage tank, causing the release. The storage facility has a Accountable Custody Transfer(ACT) meter that indicated a meter failure by a warning light at the time of the release event. Other level control devices on the storage facility include: External float level gauge and digital reading with storage levels; both devices were operational at this time. The employee did not recognize the failure and continued to unload the product. Upon unloading, the employee left the facility and returned with another load. Upon return to the facility the employee discovered the release.
column169: All employees are trained to visually check level control devices for failures, discrepancy in levels and operation of control devices. The meter failure was corrected and the storage facility returned to operation.

column168: PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED AT ABOUT 1030 PM. RESPONDER OBSERVED THE BOTTLE LEAK FROM THE CAP BECAUSE IT WASN'T ON TIGHT ENOUGH. THE RESPONDER FIRST TESTED THE PH OF THE INCIDENT AND IT WAS AN ACID(1). HE GOT THE SPILL TRAY AND LINED IT WITH THE GREEN DEEP BAG. HE THEN PUT CLAY ABSORBENT IN IT AND THEN POUR THE NITRIC ACID INTO THE LINED SPILL TRAY. HE THEN PUT IT IN SODIUM BICARBONATE MIXED IT WITH THE STIR STICK AND TESTED IT AGAIN. THE PH WAS NEUTRAL. HE THEN PROCEEDED TO GOOSE NECK IT. AT ABOUT 1045 PM THE SUBSTANCE REACTED TO THE CLAY ABSORBENT AND CARDBOARD IN THE DMP BAG CAUSING THE BAG TO SMOKE AND CATCH FIRE. MARCELO THEN GRAB THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER FROM PSC AREA AND PUT THE FIRE OUT IN THE DMP. THE PACKAGE STARED TO SMOKE AND WENT UP TO THE DMP VENT. THE BUILDING WAS EVACUATED AT 1051PM. CHAIN OF COMMAND AND HUB MANAGER JEFF GARCIA WAS NOTIFIED. A CALL WAS PLACED TO 911 AT 1057PM. THE FIRE DEPT SHOWED UP AT 11:15 PM. THEY WENT TO THE DMP AND INSPECTED WHAT WAS LEFT OF THE BOX. AT APPROX. 11:25 PM THE FIRE DEPT GAVE THE OK TO REOCCUPY THE BUILDING. JEFF GARCIA ASKED SUPERVISORS TO OPEN ALL BAY DOORS IN THE BUILDING TO HELP CLEAR SMOKE AND ODORS. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE OTHER THAT THE PACKAGE AND DMP BAG. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, ALL EMPLOYEES WERE QUESTION UPON REENTRY INTO THE BUILDING. BUILDING RESUMED WORKING AT 11:45 PM. OUTSIDE RESPONDER NRC CAME TO DISPOSE AND CLEAN DMP PROCESSING AREA AT ABOUT 12:05 AM. THE REMNANTS AN DAL LPPE THAT NRC USED WERE PUT IN A GREEN DMP BAG. THE RESPONDER THEN PROCESSED THE INCIDENT THROUGH ETT AND GOT TEMP ID.

column168: An employee of the Saint Lawrence and Atlantic Railroad reported smelling chlorine from a chlorine tank car in Pan Am Railways rail yard.  He reported it to a Pan Am Railways employee who called our operations center in North Billerica, MA.  The leak was confirmed by Pan Am Railways management and 911 services were called.  The local hazardous material team responded.  The access to the site was controlled.  The leak was identified as coming from a liquid valve packing nut, which was loose.  The packing nut was tightened and the leak stopped.  The container was tested for leaks and no other leaks were found.  Approximately 7 hours from the time of the report to the time of the securement of the leak.
column169: Better procedures for inspecting all valves and fittings on TIH rail cars.

column168: The driver of a van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was conducting a routine load check at a truck stop when he noticed a small amount of liquid dripping from the front of the trailer.  After putting a bucket under the drip, a response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A drum was found to have a pinhole leak caused by a nail in the pallet it was sitting on.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum and the trailer floor was cleaned with an absorbent material which was also swept up and put into the salvage drum, along with the material used to clean the spill from the parking lot.  The shipment then continued to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.  The state of Oklahoma DEQ was notified and assigned incident number 140784.  A followup call indicated they would not visit the site as it had all been cleaned up.

column168: On 3/9/2015 at 17:48, personnel in the CSXT Hookers Point Yard, Tampa, FL discovered UTLX 209005, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, NOS, leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Badger State Ethanol, the Florida State Watch Office report number 2015-1442, and the NRC report number 1110080 were notified.  CHEMTREC report number 2015-0309-00216.  Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the closure cap to be loose and the liquid line to be slightly open and clogged with Teflon tape between the valve ball and valve seat.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper.  Contractor personnel removed the excess Teflon tape and closed the valve, and cleaned up the spilled materials.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.  This incident did not require a special switching move.  A 7.1 is not required.     Cause Code:  NRRI: 303
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On March 10th, 2015 at 07:02 hours, personnel in the CSXT Selkirk Yard discovered TILX 191241, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the sides of the tank car coming from the top fitting area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, UET Shipping, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-03-10-00051. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont, the Glenmont branch was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that the release was from the liquid line valve, the operating handle cross shaft packing gland retainer was not tight as product was bypassing the packing and dripping onto the tank car. EPSVT tightened the packing gland retainer 1 turn and the release was secured, TILX 191241 was staged for 2 hours to verify no further release, the valve box cover was re-sealed and car was released.  Mr. Clarence Vassau, office: 720-563-7937 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. TILX 191241 was released for transport.    This incident did NOT require a special move.    Cause Code: 296 (2 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: Advised Mr. Clarence Vassau and Mr. Jonathan Reed on proper securement of products and the inspection process required to offer packages for transport under 173.31(d)(1)+(2).

A box truck containing hazardous waste arrived at the safety Kleen Caseyville, IL facility for an offload in order to transfer and consolidate waste onto a van trailer to be shipped to the intended waste disposal facility. Safety Kleen Caseyville, IL facility personnel noticed that there were two leaking cubic yard containers. A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and unloaded the two leaking cubic yard containers. The cubic yard containers were repacked into drums for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The box truck floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service. The release was reported to the Illinois Emergency Management Agency - operator: Lisa, report #2015-0285.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or breakage was observed. This release was the direct result of improper container selection and preparation. The driver will be retrained on proper container selection for solid and liquid waste streams. The shipper was notified and advised to use an appropriate UN rated container for future shipment of this waste stream.

On March 11, 2015 at 11:43, hours personnel in the CSXT Osborne Yard discovered UTLX 213406, a loaded tank car of Ethyl Acrylate, Stabilized, leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and Sasol Chemicals was notified (CHEMTREC Report 2015-0311-00157).  Matt Sams, a CSXT mechanical superintendent, found the source of the release to be due to a liquid line closure plug less than tool tight with the liquid line valve in the closed position.  The issue identified and the corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative.  The closure plug on the liquid line valve was secured to stop the release.  The car will be held until such time that a mobile repair and qualification can be made to the faulty valve or a One Time Movement Approval is obtained from the FRA.  This incident did require a special move.  A QA 7.1 will be filed.     NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80  Cause Code: 120

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: On March 18, 2015, at  17:45 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Avon Yard, Avon Indiana reported to onsite CSX Hazardous Material Managers that GATX 949, a loaded tank car of UN2672, Ammonia Solutions was leaking upon outbound inspection. Upon inspection by CSXT Hazardous Material Managers the leak was originating from the packing gland nut on the bottom outlet valve. The shipper, Terra International Canada Inc., was notified via Chemtrec, report #2015-03-18-00238 . CSXT Hazardous Material Managers found the packing gland nut finger loose and were able to tighten appropriately and secure the release. The bottom outlet valve was observed for further leaks and none were noted and the threads were in good condition. The FRA Hazardous Material Department was contacted and advised that OTMA 3 was necessary to continue in transportation. An OTMA 3 was filed, waybill was updated with necessary language and do not load stickers were affixed to both side of tank car GATX 949. This incident did not require a special move.  NARRI: 5x(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 80  Cause code: 547

column168: On March 3, 2015, a 5-gallon pail containing UN1263 Paint Related Material was damaged while being loaded on to an R&L Carriers trailer. The lid of the container was damaged resulting in the release of approximately 0.5 gallons of product to the trailer floor. Tank car BNSF 880612 in the railyard was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. A BNSF mechanical responder reported the BOV operating handle was in the closed position. The responder tool tightened 3 of 4 flange nuts at the BOV's outlet nozzle flange connection. Afterwards the commodity dripping ceased. BNSF 880612 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard over containment for additional monitoring. On 3/05/2015, BNSF 880612 was observed dripping at a slow rate and the aforementioned flange nuts were re-tightened which ebbed the dripping. On 3/12/2015 no active dripping was observed but arrangements were made to transfer the commodity from BNSF 880612. The commodity within BNSF 880612 was transferred into tank trucks on 3/24/2015 without further incident.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman reported odor emanating from an inbound entrained tank car GBRX 700136 in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected GBRX 700136. Responders reported finding GBRX 700136's liquid valve partially open with its closure plug not tool tight. Responders closed the liquid valve and applied Teflon tape to the closure plugs threaded area and secured it to a tool tight condition.  Afterwards, the vapor/odor from the closure plugs threaded connection ended. No liquid commodity was reported released, only vapor.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were notified that tank car UTLX 650502 in the railyard was found with commodity spillage at its manway nozzle area by FRA inspectors. The BNSF responders inspecting UTLX 650502 reported that 2 of 6 manway securement eyebolt nuts were not tool tight but finger loose.  Also, the manway gasket applied in the manway cover groove was deteriorated (partially torn, cracked and compressed). This gasket was removed and a new manway nozzle gasket installed. The manway cover was closed and all manway securement eyebolt nuts were properly tool tightened.  The spill amount which evaporated was estimated at one cup or less and no ground impact from spillage was observed. The Intact shipper seal was replaced by seal BNSF 06157924. Response was concluded by 1100 hrs. PDT, 3/18/2015.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

It was reported that approximately 10 gallons was released from a 330 gallon tote containing approximately 150 gallons of UN3265 GEL LP-10 due to a puncture caused by a forklift during unloading from the flatbed trailer. The release impacted the gravel lot. Absorbent pads were utilized to collect all free standing liquid on the surface of the ground. The impacted area of gravel was hand excavated.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Tanks were overfilled at Belton Fast Stop and spilled fuel due to an issue with the customers tanks.

On March 5, 2015, a Dupre Logistics tanker trailer (#22180) experienced a release of NA1993 Diesel Fuel due to a fuel overfill during transfer into a UST. Approximately 150 gallons of diesel fuel was released to the concrete fueling station. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmetnal to apply granular absorbents and pads to collect all free standing liquids. Bio-remediant was applied to the impacted concrete area thereafter. The remaining material was trans-loaded into the UST. All waste was containerized and transported for disposal by E3 Environmental personnel. No soils, drains, or waterways were impacted by this incident. The site was restored to its previous condition.

On March 10, 2015, R&L Carriers reported that approximately 3 gallons of UN1866 Resin Solution released to the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture during loading in Atlanta, GA. The damaged 55-gallon drum was placed into an overpack to prevent further release. Granular absorbents were applied to the impacted trailer floor. All impacted absorbents were collected and containerized for disposal.

On March 6, 2015, a Schneider Bulk DOT407 tanker released approximately ten gallons of NA1993 Emulsion Breaker 00757 due to a missing washout cap. The released material impacted the exterior of the tanker, the roadway below, and soil adjacent to the roadway. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for response. The washout cap was replaced and absorbents were utilized to decontaminate the impacted areas. A small area of soil was hand excavated and all waste was containerized for pending disposal.

The drum was overpacked and all impacted absorbents were collected and transported offsite for disposal.

column25: Mercuria Energy Trading Inc. by Bakken Oil Express LLC
column168: A. A BNSF unit petroleum crude oil train derailed 21 loaded tank cars while operating on main track. Cause of this derailment is currently under investigation. A fire ensued engulfing a portion of the derailed tank cars. The main fires were extinguished on 3/07/2015. Air monitoring, ground and water sampling were initiated. Impacted top soils were excavated.     Derailed tank car TILX 352017 sustained a heat induced or thermal tear at mid-shell at its A-end.  Partial commodity within was consumed in the fire that ensued after the derailment. The remaining commodity within TILX 325017 was transferred into portable frac tanks which are awaiting disposition. Afterwards, TILX 352017 deemed destroyed was cleaned and purged of hazardous material.  NOTE:DECREASED LOSS ESTIMATE-LIQUID LEVEL WAS ABOVE THE MANWAY AFTER THE HEAT TEAR; CORROBORATED BY BURN LINE.      B. A BNSF unit petroleum crude oil train derailed 21 loaded tank cars while operating on main track. Cause of this derailment is currently under investigation. A fire ensued engulfing a portion of the derailed tank cars. The main fires were extinguished on 3/07/2015. Air monitoring, ground and water sampling were initiated. Impacted top soils were excavated.       Derailed tank car TILX 352024 sustained a heat induced or thermal tear at its lower shell near its A-end. Partial commodity within was consumed in the fire that ensued after the derailment. The remaining commodity within TILX 352024 was transferred into portable frac tanks which are awaiting disposition. Afterwards, TILX 352024 deemed destroyed was cleaned and purged of hazardous material.    C. A BNSF unit petroleum crude oil train derailed 21 loaded tank cars while operating on main track. The BOV protective skid was damaged which resulted in BOV body damage above the 'shear plane' and the BOV ball dislodged. The remaining commodity within TILX 352052 was transferred into portable frac tanks which are awaiting disposition. column168: During transportation, a cracked clean out cap resulted in the release of approximately 1 liquid cup of UN1805 Phosphoric Acid to the man-way and body of the CMTV. The client supplied a replacement tanker and the material was successfully trans-loading into the replacement tanker. A contractor responded to perform the trans-loading. The contractor neutralized the released material, cleaned the impacted areas and collected all the wastes for pending disposal.

column168: On March 24, 2015, a 55-gallon drum containing UN1263 Gold Epoxy was struck by a forklift blade while being offloaded from an R&L Carriers trailer. Approximately two gallons of product was released to the trailer floor. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for cleanup activities. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon salvage container. Granular absorbent was then applied to the impacted area and worked in thoroughly. All waste was collected and containerized for pending disposal.

On March 30, 2015, a shipment of UN1993 Flammable Liquid being carried by Landstar Inway experienced a release of approximately 1 quart of material to the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched Lincoln Environmental out of Salt Lake City, UT to inspect the totes and clean the release. Two of the 14 totes were found to have loose or damaged caps. The caps were re-secured and the trailer floor was cleaned completely. All waste was containerized and transported for proper disposal.

column168: On March 11, 2015, R&L reported that approximately 2 oz. of UN1760 Corrosive Liquid material was released to a 15 ft. x 15 ft. area of a trailer (#LE0442). The release was due to puncture of the 6-gallon pail from a sharp object or adjacent freight. ERTS dispatched NRC Environmental to neutralize the release and apply granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and a minimal area of asphalt below. All impacted absorbents were collected and containerized for disposal. The damaged pail was placed into a 30-gallon poly overpack drum for continued transport after clean-up was completed.

column168: On 03/23/15 at 1100 hours personnel at CSXT Mile Post 000 568 located just outside of the Georgia Pacific plant located at 32224 HIGHWAY 31 Brewton, AL discovered GATX5930, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid leaking from the pressure relief device. The car was isolated and the shipper, Alabama Environmental Management, the NRC, and Chemtrec were notified (CHEMTREC Report # 1111506). United States Environmental Services, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the rupture disk had burst. The shipper, Barry Lindley (304-357-1877) was updated. The contractor, USES, replaced the blown rupture disk and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.        NAR Cause Code: 1004  Frangible disc ruptured; surge suppressor present    2(5+3+5) x (2+0) = 52 NARRI     Brewton, Alabama  03/23/2015  GATX5930  Sulfuric Acid

column168: CTCX 733434 was observed leaking contents from the manway area upon arrival at PTRA North Yard on Thursday, March 26, 2015 at approximately 5:00 AM. The area was immediately secured and M&M Protection, LLC was dispatched to investigate the cause and secure the railcar.  Upon arrival M&M found that all manway bolts were loose, no security seal was applied to the manway bolts and no gasket was installed prior to shipping the railcar.  M&M installed a shoulder gasket, closed and secured the manway and applied a security seal. The car was then moved to a storage track where it could be decontaminated. M&M used a microbug solution, Pure Green, applied with a pressure washer under heat to decontaminate the product on the sides and top of the tank car. The scene was cleared at approximately 10:30 AM.
column169: The shipper, Eighty Eight Oil, LLC, was notified of the incident and directed the PTRA to the loader of the car, GBW Railcar services.  They have been notified of the incident. At this time the PTRA has not received any action taken to prevent future incidents from the shipper or loader of the railcar.

column168: On March 9, 2015 at 1300 ET, approximately 1 pint of material released from a 55-gallon steel drum to the trailer floor and the concrete parking area below due to an apparent pallet nail puncture. A cleanup contractor was dispatched to the site to remediate the release. The puncture was patched and the damaged drum was over-packed for continued shipment. One 5-gallon bucket of impacted absorbents and PPE was generated from this response which the contractor took for pending disposal.

column25: SPECIAL MATERIALS COMPANY, INDUSTRIAL SERVICES DIVISION
column168: The Chemsolv, Inc. driver picked up 12 drums of Monochlorotoluene (MCT) from Special Materials Company at 369 Little Dude Avenue, Kershaw, SC. He then went directly to his next stop Guardian Industries Corporation where he found that the MCT had leaked in the trailer and while there a small amount dripped out of the trailer onto the driveway. Absorbent pillows were used to remove the spilled material. There was no safety issue or environmental impact from the small spill. Further investigation found only one drum had leaked and the cause was a loose bung plug. The other 11 drums were checked and also found to have bung plugs not adequately tightened. The bung plugs were all tightened prior to leaving Guardian Industries Corporation. The final destination for the MCT was Chemsolv, Inc. 120 E. Mount Gallant Road, Rock Hill, SC. The drum was weighed once received at Chemsolv, Inc. and determined to have lost approximately 34 pounds.
column169: Special Materials Company performed a root cause analysis and determined the cause to be human error. The bung plugs were "not torqued to 22 ft-lbs after completing the repackaging operation. The immediate corrective action was to re-torque the bung plugs on all like MCT drums in inventory. The corrective action to prevent recurrence is to review and make changes as necessary to non-standard work instructions and drum closure procedures.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; O-Ring or Seals
column168: Driver was pulled over by PD because of product leaking from the overflow reservoir tank. A valve to the air separator had been left open by the driver. The open valve, in combination with leaking seals on the air separator, allowed the product to over-pressurize the reservoir tank and leak during transportation. The driver pulled into a restaurant parking lot. The Fire Department evacuated the restaurant out of an abundance of caution to minimize the risk of fire, not due to concerns with direct exposure.
column169: The driver has been trained to close the product valve during transportation, and to drain the reservoir tank on a regular basis. The seals on the air separator have been replaced.

column168: Upon arrival at the relay terminal, a leaking drum was discovered inside the trailer. column169: The use of proper dunnage to protect the drums could have prevented this release. The employee responsible was counseled per company policy. This incident will be used as an example for future training and meeting topic discussions.

On March 12, 2015, a Howard Sheppard Inc. tanker trailer (#LT345) experienced a loss of approximately 2,110 gallons of UN3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, NOS (Aluminum Sulfate Solution) as the result of a fitting on the customer's tank failing during unloading operations. No drains or waterways were impacted as a result of this release. The released material impacted the customer's gravel lot. First Call Environmental conducted emergency response/containment and environmental remediation measures in order to restore the area to its previous condition. All contaminated gravel and absorbents were containerized and transported for proper disposal by First Call.

column168: Tank trailer was loaded at Dow Corning in Carrollton, KY.  The driver picked up the loaded tanker, and stopped outside the main gate to take an "off-duty" rest period.  When he came back "on-duty", the driver did a pre-trip vehicle inspection and noticed a small leak of product (approximately 1 kg).  The driver notified Laidlaw dispatch and the customer (Dow Corning) was notified.  The spill was cleaned up by the driver and Dow staff.  The driver then went to pick up another empty tank, and the product was transferred from the leaky tank, to the new one.  The transfer was done at Dow Corning by their personnel. The leaky tank was taken to Polar in Louisville, KY for repairs.  A small crack was detected in the inner barrel, underneath the stainless steel ring.  The crack could not be detected from the exterior.
column169: The tank in question was due for it's annual inspection in May of 2015, and this crack in the barrel would have been discovered.  All of our tank trailers are inspected every 60 days, in regards to exterior and running items, and internal pressure tests are done annually.

column168: THE REPORT IS FILED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR 171.16(A)(5). A UPS DRIVER WAS IN THE MIDDLE OF HIS DELIVERY ROUTE WHEN HE SMELLED SMOKE, CAUSING HIM TO PULL OVER TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND CALL 911. WHEN THE EDEN PRAIRIE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE, THEY OPENED THE BOX IN QUESTION, CONFIRMING THAT THE FIRE PUT ITSELF OUT BEFORE THEY HAD ARRIVED, THE FIRE WAS CAUSED BY THE POSITIVE AND NEGATIVE CLAMPS OF THE 12 VOLT POWER SUPPLY 1700 PEAK AMP JUMP STARTED TOUCHING EACH OTHER. THEY CREATED ENOUGH HEAT TO IGNITE THE NEWSPAPER THAT WAS BEING USED AS PACKING MATERIAL. THE JUMP STARTER CONTAINED A SEALED NON-SPILLAGE LEAD ACID BATTERY, BUT THERE WERE NO EXTERIOR MARKINGS ON THE PACKAGE TO INDICATE IT CONTAINED A NON-SPILLABLE LEAD ACID BATTERY. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR DAMAGES, OTHER THAN THE PACKAGE AND THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE.  THE DRIVER WAS IN THE MIDDLE OF HIS DELIVERY ROUTE WHEN HE SMELLED SMOKE. There was a significant release based on the location of the damage that occurred to the tote (bottom corner). Once the area was secured, the hazmat was properly identified and the spill was contained using on site spill control products. The SDS data sheets were reviewed and the spilled product was properly placed in recovery drums along with the used spill control supplies. The drum will be properly disposed of by contracted regulated hazardous waste carrier.
column169: This particular IBS plastic tote only had the aluminum cage / bars on it, it didn't have the corner protectors (metal and or hard plastic). If this tote had the corner protectors on it wouldn't have been pierced by the wood pallet of freight that was being loaded onto the same trailer next to the tote. The employee who damaged the tote was properly disciplined and given refresher training.     In my opinion the IBS plastic totes need to been designed better to have the capability to withstand greater wear and tear especially on the transportation end. All of the plastic totes should have the protected metal corners, the cage bars don't protect the corners, which are the spot to be most likely damaged during the loading & unloading of freight that is on the same trailer.

column168: Leaking shipments were reported at the building 2 truck dock at DHL Express, 236 Wendell H Ford Blvd, Erlanger, KY 41018 on 3/31/2015 at approx 14:47. The shipments were (at that time) comprised of multiple cans of aerosol suntan lotion packed into retail display boxes, stacked on a wooden skid and completely covered with opaque, black plastic shrink-wrap, hiding the contents. There were a total of 1152 aerosol cans on the skid. Cause of damage is unknown. There is speculation that the shrink wrap was not as tight at the bottom of the skid, causing a box of the aerosols to shift while in transit and partially slip out from underneath the black plastic. When the skid was removed from the truck, it is believed cans slipped out and three cans were crushed. Contents lost is described as 22.5 ozs.There are a total of 5 skids of this freight sitting in the DG area at DHL Express, all completely enclosed by the black, opaque plastic shrink-wrap. Transportation via truck was confirmed.

column168: On 3/25/2015 at 18:22, personnel in the CSXT Edgewood Yard discovered GATX 200410, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids, N. O. S. (Crude Sulfateturpentine), leaking from the reclosing pressure relief device due to an overloaded tank car.  The car was isolated and the shipper Domtar Paper Company, the Florida State Watch Office (report number 2015-1857), and the NRC (report number 1111727) were notified.  CHEMTREC report number  2015-0325-00222.  Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car leaking from the reclosing pressure relief device.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Karen).  Contractor personnel offloaded 500 gallons of the product and decontaminated the car.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.  This incident did not require a special switching move or a 7.1. column168: Tank car NATX 300176 was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area while in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspecting NATX 300176 reported the drip source was at the bottom outlet's closure cap's (BOC) threaded connection. The responder removed the BOC and replaced its inner gasket. The BOC was secured and the dripping ceased. Commodity drips atop the ballast evaporated. The responder also reported that when the BOC was removed some commodity was observed by-passing the closed BOV. NATX 300176 was carefully moved and placed over retention pans in the railyard. FRA-15030166 (OTMA-1) was granted to transport the non-leaking NATX 300176 to destination for unloading and afterwards to a qualified repair facility for appropriate BOV repairs.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman inspecting a BNSF outbound train consist in the railyard reported residue tank car PPRX 28569 emanating a commodity odor. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting PPRX 28569 reported finding its manway closure unsecured. No liquid commodity release was evident. The applied manway nozzle gasket was protruding from the manway closure. All six manway securement eyebolts were not secured (three were not tool tight and three were not applied/hanging downward). The manway nozzle gasket that was out of position and crimped was replaced by a new manway nozzle gasket. All six manway securement eyebolts were properly positioned and their eyebolt nuts tool tightened which ended any further vapor/odor release. Securement was completed by 1000 hrs. PDT, 3/22/2015. The manway closure was sealed with seal BNSF 06157920.

column168: Tank car SRIX 30068 located at the repair track (for a coupler system draft gear lug defect) in the railyard was observed leaking commodity from its top fitting area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting SRIX 30068 reported finding its liquid valve partially open with its valve port closure plug only hand tight. Responders closed the liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug which ended the commodity release from the closure plugs threaded connection by 1400 hrs. PDT, 3/22/2015. No ground impact from spillage was observed and spillage on SRIX 30068's side shell evaporated. Intact shipper seal CALUMET 036100 at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal BNSF 06157820.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ERTS was contacted by Barb Sayden of Schneider National regarding a cargo release. It was reported that a Schneider National truck was stopped for a DOT inspection, a pallet of batteries were found to be leaking inside the trailer. Truck and trailer were placed out of service by the DOT pending clean up of the release. It was reported that an estimated 1-2 gallons of battery acid has released inside the trailer. No drains soils or waterways are reported to be impacted by this release.  A network contractor was dispatched to the site and cleaned the released material.

THE PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. IT APPEARS WHEN THE DRIVER COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY AND DISCONNECTED HIS HOSE, THERE WAS SOME RESIDUAL DIESEL FUEL STILL IN THE HOSE THAT SPILLED ONTO THE SURFACE. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS SPILLED. KROPP ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: PETRO CHEMICAL TRANSORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On March 31, 2015 at 01:41 hours, personnel at CSXT Barr Yard discovered UTLX 212519, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have released product from the pressure relief device area. The car was isolated and the Shipper, UET Shipping, LLC was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2015-03-31-00022. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, the Schererville, IN branch office was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection it was determined the rod located inside the pressure relief device had broken.  The car was secured to prevent additional leakage until receiving feedback from shipper.      A HAZMATHOLD was placed on UTLX 212519.  The car will need to have approximately 200 gallons of petroleum crude oil to be removed.  Then the PRD will need to be replaced and either an OTMA-3 will be submitted or it can be bubble tested in the field for future movement.      Cause Code: 418 at 2 points  NARRI: 5 (5 + 5 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: AT TIME OF FILLING TOTE BUNG WAS NOT PROPERLY TIGHTENED WITH BUNG TOOL. IN TRANSIT BUNG WORKED LOOSE AND SLOSH OF PRODUCT CAUSED SMALL SPILL OVER TOP OF TOTE THAT RAN ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. PRODUCT DID NOT LEAK OUTSIDE OF TRAILER. TRAILER FLOOR AND TOTE CLEANED UP ON SITE AND CLEAN-UP PRODUCTS AND SPILL PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  BUNG WAS PROPERLY TIGHTENED BEFORE UNLOADING TOTE.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER USES PROPER TOOLS TO TIGHTEN BUNGS AT TIME OF LOADING PRODUCT AND RECHECKED AT TIME OF LOADING TOTES FOR TRANSIT.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: Approximately 10 gallons of UN2794 battery acid was released from (1) 2,000 lb industrial battery during unloading activities. It was reported that the blocking and bracing straps broke, causing the battery to fall off the pallet. A forklift driver attempted to up-right the battery with the fork lift, and caused damage to 2 cells resulting in the release. The release impacted the trailer floor. The released material was neutralized with sodium bicarbonate and collected in (1) 30 gallon drum.

AT 7:40 PM SUPERVISOR CHARLES BURTON CALLED A LEAKING PACKAGE OVER THE RADIO ON PF1. SOMETHING LEAKED ON HIM FROM THE PF. IT STARTED BURING HIS SKIN SLIGHTLY SO HE WASHED IT IMMEDIATELY WITH LOTS OF WATER. THE BELT WAS SMOLDERING, SUPERVISOR DANA COOK AND THE RMP JOHN WOLSKY WERE ON THE BELT LOOKING FOR THE PACKAGE. JOHN WOLSKY WENT THROUGH THE PRIMARY ON THE BELT AND FOUND A LEAKING AND SMOLDERING PACKAGE ON THE PF BELT. THE RESPONDER WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY AND WAS THEN TOLD WHERE EXACTLY THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS. HE SUITED UP WITH SCBA, COLLECTED THE PACKAGE AND BROUGHT IT OUTSIDE OF PD 3. JOHN WOLSKY THEN WENT OVER THE BELT, CLEANING THE SPILL, WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE. AT THE SAME TIME, THE SORT MANAGER, SAFETY SUPERVISOR, PE WERE ALL NOTIFIED AND ON SCENE. THE CHAIN OF COMMAND WAS FOLLOWED FOR AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT AND THE BELT WAS RUNNING AGAIN AT 8:30. AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER WAS CALLED AT 8:45 P.M. AND THE PACKAGE WAS CLEANED UP AND CONTAINED AT 12:30 PM.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A BNSF train operating on main track derailed 13 rail cars. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a load shift of steel pipe on a bulkhead flatcar that subsequently fell off the flatcar. Tank car UTLX 201252 derailed on its side and commodity released via its Midland 75 psig set reclosing pressure relief valve (PRV) that became stuck in an open position due to damage to the top portion of the PRV.  BNSF and contract responders were able to close/reseat the PRV which ended the commodity release from UTLX 201252. The remaining commodity within UTLX 201252 was transferred into tank trucks on 4/06-07/2015. Afterwards, UTLX 201252 was cleaned and purged of hazardous material. The damaged UTLX 201252 was deemed destroyed.  Pooled ground spillage was vacuumed and impacted ground soils were excavated. Recovered liquids and excavated soils are awaiting appropriate disposal
column169: No additional comments.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: An odor was reported emanating from an area surrounding several tank cars located in the railyard. Investigation into the odor source concluded that residue tank car PPRX 28544 was emanating a commodity odor. PPRX 28544 was isolated in the railyard. BNSF and contract responders reported that 2 of 6 manway securement eyebolts were not applied (hanging downward) and the other 4 securement eyebolts were loose (eyebolt securement nuts not tool tight). Responders opened the manway cover to inspect the manway gasket condition and the applied manway gasket was deemed serviceable.  The sealing surfaces of the manway cover and the manway gasket were cleaned to ensure a good closure seal. The manway securement eyebolts were properly positioned and their eyebolt nuts tool tightened. Afterwards, no further residue commodity odor/vapor was detected and this was confirmed by the responder's Multi-Rae VOC meter.  There was no liquid release associated with this incident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported tank car BNSF 880407 in the railyard leaking from its bottom outlet area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting BNSF 880407 reported commodity dripping from the mounting flange connection for the bottom outlet nozzle. Responders slowed the dripping by tightening the flange bolt nuts.  The operating rod for the top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) was inspected and found loose and in a partially open position. The TOBOV operating rod was closed approximately 1 1/2 turns which stopped the dripping from the bottom outlet nozzle flange. Additional packing material was applied at the TOBOV operating rod and the packing nut tightened.  BNSF 880407 at its destination was placed for unloading and unloaded without further incident. After unloaded, BNSF 880407 was directed to a qualified repair facility for inspection and necessary repairs to the TOBOV and bottom outlet fittings. Absorbent padding was placed atop ground spillage and contract responders arrived to complete the remediation of the ground spillage. All remediation and cleaning materials recovered were stored on-site and properly labeled awaiting future disposal.

column168: ERTS was notified of a release of 10 gallons of UN2582, Ferric chloride. The tank was leaking half way up the body of the containment portion of the tanker from a small hole. The release was potentially due to erosion of the rubber lining allowing the contents of the tanker to react with the stainless steel shell resulting in corrosion and subsequent deterioration of the outer shell.  Onsite personnel put buckets underneath to catch any excess liquid. The release impacted the asphalt lot of the facility. No soil or drains were impacted by the release. The contractor dispatched by ERTS responded to the incident by temporarily patching the quarter sized hole and trans loading the ferric chloride to a replacement tanker when it  arrived. Absorbents were used to thoroughly remove all standing liquid from the asphalt and loaded into three 55 gallon drums.

ON 03/10/2015 AT APPROXIMATELY 08:00 AM TRIAD TRANSPORT DRIVER RALPH L. THOMPSON EXITED THE FREEWAY ONTO THE ACCESS ROAD. WITH OTHER VEHICLES ON HIS RIGHT HE ATTEMPTED TO STAY TO THE LEFT AFTER ENTERING THE ACCESS ROAD. HE GOT TOO CLOSE TO THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT AND ALLOWED THE LEFT FRONT WHEEL TO SLIP OFF THE EDGE OF ROADWAY. THERE HAD BEEN HEAVY RAINS IN THE AREA RECENTLY AND THE GROUND WAS VERY SOFT. THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO GET THE TRUCK BACK UP ON THE PAVEMENT AS IT WAS SO SOFT THE WHEELS/TIRES BEGAN TO SINK INTO THE GROUND IMMEDIATELY AND CAUSED THE TRUCK/TRAILER TO ROLL OVER ON THE LEFT SIDE.  THE ROLL-OFF BOX CONTAINING CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS COVERED WITH A CANVAS TARP THAT FAILED WHEN THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER ONTO THE LEFT SIDE. APPROXIMATELY ONE YARD OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED FROM THE BOX ONTO THE GRASSY DITCH AT THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY.    MILLLER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES FORM CORPUS CHRISTIE, TX WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED CONTENTS OF THE BOX. THEY WERE ON SITE AND BEGAN ASSESSMENT BY APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AM. THEY USED A FRONT END LOADER TO SCOOP THE PRODUCT INTO THE BOX AFTER IT WAS SET UP ONTO THE PAVEMENT BY A WRECKER SERVICE. CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED BY APPROXIMATELY 7:00 PM.

column168: 4x55g drums were palletized on a loaded truck trailer. Using a forklift to offload the pallet from the trailer, the pallet flexed and one of the drums slipped off the pallet and landed on its side. The drum lid tweaked to a point and liquid leaked out onto the concrete. The leaking drum was uprighted immediately and absorbant used immediately to stop the material spread and absorb any odors. The spill was contained and under control in approximately 3 minutes.  There was no package failure before being handled for offload. The damaged drum was overpacked and continued on to its original destination.
column169: PALLETIZED MATERIAL WILL BE SECURED TO PALLETS USING STRAPPING OR BANDING TO PREVENT MOVEMENT. HEAVY DRUMS WILL NOT BE PALLETIZED IN GROUPS OF FOUR PER PALLET.  PALLETS WILL BE THROUGHLY INSPECTED FOR USE WHEN HEAVY DRUMS ARE PREPARED FOR LOADING.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS PUMPING PREMIUM TANK OUT BECAUSE OF A PREVIOUS PRODUCT MIX. IN DOING SO HE FILLED THE REGULAR TANK PAST 90% CAUSING THE OVERFILL PROTECTION TO ACTIVATE. THE BALL CHECK ACTIVATED CAUSING THE TANK TO BUILD PRESSURE AND PUSH PRODUCT OUT THE DROP TUBE. SPRAYING PRODUCT ENTERED DRIVER'S EYES AND HE HAD TREATMENT AT LOCAL HOSPITAL.
column169: Driver was re-trained and re-certified on proper pump out/over procedures.

column168: Driver was unloading diesel into tank 71 at the Roseville Bulk Plant. While unloading the 90% warning alarm came on. Driver continued to unload product because he thought it would fit. Overfill alarm activated and driver noticed the overflow of product. Driver notified his supervisor immediately. Supervisor quickly assessed the incident and found that the entire amount of the spilled product was held within the bulk facilities concrete walled containment. Supervisor notified Lube Tech Liquid Recyclers to clean product out of the containment. LLR was able to use the revacuum truck to vac all of the product out and recycle it at the Lube Tech facility. Residual product on the tank, valves and concrete floor were wiped down with absorbent pads and recycled.
column169: Lubrication Technologies has terminated this driver for not following company policies and procedures in regards to unloading into bulk facility tanks. Also all other drivers have been through a retraining session in regards to loading and unloading at bulk facilities. Lube-Tech will be exploring a automatic shutoff system when tank hits a certain level to prevent overflow incidents.

column43: UNDYED ULTRA LOW SULFUR DIESEL, 15 PPM OR LESS SULFUR
column168: DRIVER OF FUEL TRANSPORT TRUCK WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL TO AN 8,000 GALLON DIESEL FUEL TANK. THE DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED 132 GALLONS MORE THAN THE EXISTING PRODUCT IN THE TANK AND ADDITIONAL 1,700 GALLONS ON HIS TRUCK WOULD FIT. THE 132 GALLONS WAS PUSHED OUT THE VENT OF THE TANK, RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK ONTO THE CEMENT PAD. IT THEN RAN OFF THE CEMENT PAD ONTO THE DIRT AND DOWN THE EMBANKMENT INTO A WASH. THIS WASH WAS DRY AND IS 250 YARDS AWAY FROM THE WATER IN THE COLORADO RIVER. THE FUEL NEVER TOUCHED ANY WATER AND WAS CLEANED UP BEFORE IT RAINED OR WATER RAN THROUGH THE WASH AGAIN. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS LESS THAN ONE MINUTE AND WHEN THE OVERFILL WAS FOUND, THE DRIVER TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION TO SHUT DOWN THE PUMP AND ALL THE VALVES IN THE SYSTEM. THE DRIVER AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PLACED ABSORBENT MATERIALS IN AREAS TO SOAK UP THE PRODUCT AND KEEP FROM DRAINING ADDITIONAL PRODUCT ONTO THE DIRT.
column169: To prevent this from happening again in the future we have done three things:   1. Instructed our dispatch department to ensure the amounts they dispatch will fit in the tank.  2. Retrained our drivers on the procedures for pumping off a load of fuel, which includes determining that the load will fit before they begin pumping off the fuel.  3. Improved communications between the tank owners, our drivers, and our dispatchers. Overall we improved our operating procedures.

column168: A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Services was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 1 quart of material had  escaped from a crack near the top of the container.  Upon examination of the drum, it appeared to have built up pressure to cause a small crack in the drum.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all containers used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column168: Trimac called ERTS about a release of UN2735 "MPCA (Mixed Polycycloaliphatic Amines)" from a fixed 407 tanker unit at a facility in Haysville, KS.  It was reported that the DOT 407 was hissing and they decided to transfer the product to another trailer.  During the transfer process, the contractor's pump failed to work properly resulting in approximately 300 gallons of material to the concrete containment area at the facility; no material was reported to have breached containment wall; no impact to the environment has been made.  ERTS dispatched a network contractor to respond to the clean up.

AT11:25AM, A GULFMARK ENERGY DRIVER CHAD KELLY ARRIVED AT THE BEAUMONT LOCATION FOR OFFLOADING. GULFMARK DRIVER CHAD KELLY HOOKED HIS HOSE TO THE CALUMET TRANSLOADER, AND STARTED HIS PUMP FOR THE EXTRACTION PROCESS. CALUMET EMPLOYEE BART BENDY WAS ON SITE BUT, NOT PRESENT AT THE TRANSLOADER. THE TRANSLOADER WAS NOT IN PROPER POSITION INSIDE THE RAILCAR FOR EXTRACTION. AT 11:30AM, GULFMARK DRIVER CHAD KELLY STARTED HIS PUMP WITH THE TRANSLOADER NOT IS POSITION. HE RELEASED 100 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL AT THE LOCATION (N 30*02.838' W 094*04.416). THE PUMP WAS RUNNING FOR 5 TO 8 SECONDS DURING THE RELEASE.  GULFMARK DRIVER CHAD KELLY ALERTED CALUMET EMPLOYEE BART BENDY OF THE INCIDENT. THEY IMMEDIATELY PLACED OIL BOOMS AND PADS TO QUARANTINE THE RELEASE. AT 11:40AM, THEY NOTIFIED THERE SUPERVISORS. THEN WHO THEN NOTIFIED MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL FOR CLEANUP.  AT 1:00PM, MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED. THEY ARRIVED WITH A VACUUM TRUCK TO REMOVE ALL STANDING CRUDE OIL. THEY THEN PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AND ABSORBENT GRAVEL DOWN TO REMOVE ALL REMAINING RESIDUE. LATER THEY REMOVED ALL CONTAMINATED GRAVEL AND ABSORBENT GRAVEL THEN A DEGREASER WAS SPRAYED ON THE AREA. NEW GRAVEL WAS BROUGHT IN OVER THE AREA RETURNING IT TO ITS ORIGINAL STATE. SAMPLES WERE TAKEN OF THE EXCAVATED CLEANED AREA AND A BACKGROUND SAMPLE WAS TAKEN. SAMPLES WERE CLEAN AND CLEAN UP MEETS TRRP CLEAN UP STANDARD.
column169: TRUCK DRIVERS AND CALUMET EMPLOYEE MUST BOTH BE PRESENT BEFORE UNLOADING CAN OCCUR.

column168: A BNSF yard crew reported tank car PROX 41731 in the railyard leaking liquid from its top fitting area onto its side shell. PROX 41731 was cordoned-off in the railyard and containment was placed under PROX 41731. Inspection by a BNSF mechanical responder revealed commodity emanating from PROX 41731's top style reclosing pressure relief valve (PRV) which is indicative of a volume overload. The responder noted that commodity release at the PRV was slowing and nearing a stop. PROX 41731 was carefully moved to a location in the railyard to accomplish a commodity reduction into a tank truck.  Commodity reduction and cleaning of PROX 41731's shell was completed by 0100 hrs. PDT, 3/31/2015. Impacted ballast and ground soils were excavated.
column169: The shipper was notified of the volume overload condition of PROX 41731 and the shipper responded that they have already rectified the problem leading to incorrect loading calculations.

Private Carriage driver arrived at Chaosland in Ulysses, KS at approximately 7:30 AM and started unloading at 8:05 AM. At approximately 9 AM the vent on the customer's tank did not operate properly which resulted in the failure of the customer's transfer piping. Approximately 1600 gallons of HCL spilled from the customer's tank into the concrete containment area. The driver immediately stopped the unloading process and notified the customer. The customer accepted responsibility for the spill and is coordinating all cleanup activities. No injuries occurred. No further incident occurred.
column169: The spill was immediately cleaned up by the customer. No further incident has occurred.

column168: Tank car GATX 57735 in the railyard was reported with some wetness and dried commodity staining on its side shell. Minimal ground impact from spillage was observed.  BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders  inspecting GATX 57735 reported  all flange bolt nuts on the top fittings were not tool tight: 4 blind flange bolt nuts on the vapor line (with vapor line's closure plug hand tight), 4 mounting flange bolt nuts on the vacuum relief valve's mounting base plate and 8 bolt nuts on the fill hole blind flange. The responder's tool tightened all flange bolt nuts and the loose plug. A contract responder was called to clean the spillage from GATX 57735 and to re-check securement.  The contract responders reported the vacuum relief valve (VRV) was emanating vapors when GATX 57735 was pressured-up. The faulty VRV was removed and the vacated VRV orifice was secured.  Spillage on GATX 57735 was neutralized and cleaned. Spent cleaning materials were placed into a disposal drum for appropriate disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: THE AIR LIQUIDE VEHICLE WAS AT A CUSTOMER'S SITE UNLOADING PRODUCT AT THE PROPER PRESSURE, WHEN ONE OF THE TWO BURST DISK FAILED. IMMEDIATELY UPON SEEING THE INITIAL BURST DISK FAIL, THE DRIVER FOLLOWED PROTOCOL AND ENGAGED THE DIVERTER VALVE, WHICH DIRECTED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT TO THE SECONDARY BURST DISK LINE. DUE TO A SMALL PIECE OF THE RUPTURED BURST DISK, THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO FULLY DIVERT THE FLOW OF PRODUCT THROUGH TO THE SECONDARY BURST DISK LINE. THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS DEPOT MANAGEMENT FOR FURTHER DIRECTION. DEPOT MANAGEMENT CONTACTED A THIRD PARTY PROVIDER, WHO RESPONDED TO THE AIR LIQUIDE VEHICLE AT THE CUSTOMER'S SITE AND WAS ABLE TO GET THE DIVERTER TO ENGAGE FULLY TO THE SECONDARY BURST DISK. THE PRESSURE OF THE VEHICLE WAS REDUCE AND THEN TAKEN TO THE THIRD PARTY PROVIDER FOR THE NECESSARY REPAIRS.
column169: REGARDING RECOMMENDATIONS OR ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF THIS EVENT, AIR LIQUIDE WILL CONTINUE ITS CURRENT TRAINING AND PROTOCOL REGARDING ACTIONS TAKEN IN THE EVEN OF A BURST DISK FAILURE. AIR LIQUIDE HAS REVISE ITS LIQUID HYDROGEN TRAILER SPECIFICATIONS TO ADD ADDITIONAL INLINE SAFETIES WHICH ELIMINATE THE NEED FOR BURST DISKS. AIR LIQUIDE WILL PLACE ADDITIONAL BURST DISKS ON CURRENT TRAILERS TO BE USED IN CASE OF INSTALLED BURST DISK FAILURE.

column168: On 03/12/2015 at 1601hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Cleveland Ohio Terminal discovered MRKU814310, a loaded container of UN2234, Chlorobenzotrifluorides,  3, III, in 55 gallon drums leaked approximately 1gallon of liquid from rear of container with minimum drops on asphalt pavement. The container was isolated and NRC, report#1110453 and OH EPA report#1503-18-0434 were notified. The shipper, Maersk Inc representative Brian Stabler and Athanasia Voulgaris with Valspar were notified by CSXI Customer Service. SUNPRO Services, CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found two 55 gallon drums leaked less than 1 gallon of product due to loose top head-bungs. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the leak with tightening the loose bongs, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the material. The original freight container with proper load/block/brace was released to the shipper.       This incident did not require a special switching move.   This incident did not require a Form 7.1..

column168: ERTS was contacted by Matthew Crocket of R&L Carriers ATL terminal regarding a cargo release. It was reported that when terminal personnel went to unload trailer OAO565 a pallet of UN1814 potassium hydroxide was found to be spilled. Caller reports that of the 24 5gal pails on the skid, 8 were tipped over and leaking due to improper blocking and bracing of the shipment. Release is estimated to be 1-2 gallons inside the trailer. No soils, drains or waterways were reported to be impacted by the release. At this time there is no regulatory reporting required for this incident as the amount released is known and has not exceeded the RQ of 1000lbs. A network contractor was dispatched and cleaned the spillage.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: DESCRIPTION OF WHAT HAPPENED AND HOW IT HAPPENED.    A PLANT LAB TECHNICIAN WAS ASSISTING A DELIVERY TRUCK DRIVER IN OFFLOADING A ROUTINE TRUCKLOAD OF SULFURIC ACID TO THE COOLING TOWER SULFURIC ACID STORAGE TANK.  THE PLANT'S 8,797 GALLON ACID TANK IS LOCATED ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE PROPERTY, ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE COOLING TOWERS (SEE ATTACHMENT 1).  PRIOR TO STARTING THE OFFLOADING PROCESS, THE TANK LEVEL INDICATOR READ 42.6% AVAILABLE CAPACITY WHICH CALCULATED TO 3,748 GALLONS OF AVAILABLE CAPACITY IN THE ACID TANK.  THE QUANTITY OF SULFURIC ACID ORDERED AND IN THE TANKER WAS 3,108 GALLONS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 9:15 AM, NEAR THE END OF THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE TANK LEVEL INDICATOR SHOWED 7% AVAILABLE CAPACITY (~600 GALLONS) REMAINING IN THE TANK.  THE TRUCK WAS VERY CLOSE TO BEING EMPTY WHEN THE SULFURIC ACID BEGAN COMING OUT OF THE VENT PIPE.  THE LAB TECH OVERSEEING THE PROCESS SAW THE PRODUCT COMING OUT OF THE TANK'S VENT AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DRIVER TO SHUT DOWN THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUTDOWN THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  ONCE THE OFFLOADING PROCESS WAS SHUTDOWN, THE SPILLAGE STOPPED WITHIN SECONDS.  THE VENT ON THE ACID TANK IS DIRECTED ONTO THE GROUND, WHICH PREVENTED SPRAY FORM OCCURRING.  AN ESTIMATED 200-300 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID WERE SPILLED TO THE GROUND.    THE TANK LEVEL INDICATOR WAS INSTALLED IN THE SPRING OF 2014 AND WAS LAST CALIBRATED AT THAT TIME, UPON INVESTIGATION; THE TANK LEVEL INDICATOR IS BELIEVED TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE SPILLAGE:    * THE QUANTITY ORDERED WAS VERIFIED AGAINST THE QUANTITY RECEIVED.  * THE INITIAL READING OF THE TANK VOLUME SHOWED ROOM IN THE TANK TO HOLD WHAT WAS IN THE TANKER.  * THE LEVEL INDICATOR READ 7% VOLUME REMAINING IN THE TANK WHEN IT WAS FULL.    ATTACHMENT 2 - SHOW THE BILL OF LADING FOR THE DELIVERY
column169: DESCRIPTION OF CLEANUP AND PREVENTIVE ACTION    (ATTACHMENT 3) CONTAINS A COPY OF THE SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR SULFURIC ACID    CLEANUP OF THE AFFECTED AREA WAS COMPLETED WITHIN TWELVE HOURS OF THE SPILL, AND THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FORM THE SITE ON APRIL 8, 2015 (SEE BILL OF LADING, ATTACHMENT 4) FOR DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE REGULATORY REQUIREMENTS.    PREVENTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN AND PLANNED BY HAVANA POWER PLANT ARE:  * A PLASTIC CATCH BASIN (CONTAINMENT) HAS BEEN ADDED UNDERNEATH THE VENT TO CATCH ANY OVERFLOW FORM THE TANK IN THE FUTURE.  * IN FUTURE UNLOADING PROCESSES, THE TANK FILLING WILL END WHEN THE TANK LEVEL INDICATION SHOWS 15 PERCENT AVAILABLE CAPACITY (~1,300 GALLONS) REMAINING IN THE TANK.  *A NEW LEVEL INDICATOR EQUIPPED WITH VISUAL AND AUDIBLE ALARMS HAS BEEN PURCHASED AND WILL BE INSTALLED.  * A PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE WORK ORDER HAS BEEN ADDED TO HAVANA'S SYSTEM TO CALIBRATE ANNUALLY THE TANK LEVEL INDICATOR.  * THE POSSIBLE ADDITION OF A SIGHT GLASS WILL BE EVALUATED AGAINST THE POTENTIAL FOR SPILL ASSOCIATED WITH THE SIGHT GLASS (THE SIGHT GLASS ITSELF CAN POSE A SPILL RISK).

column17: CONSOLIDATED EDISON OF NEW YORK, INC.
column25: CONSOLIDATED EDISON OF NEW YORK, INC.
column43: LEAD CONTAMINATED SEDIMENT/WATER MIXTURE FROM CLEANING UNDERGROUND ELECTRICAL STRUCTURES
column168: The incident was not caused by package or equipment failure, but by operator error. The truck operator mistakenly opened the back hatch of the cargo tank on vactor truck # 61076, causing approximately 40 gallons of lead-contaminated sediment/water to spill onto the surface of Chatterton Avenue, in Bronx County, New York.  Approximately 25 gallons of the spilled liquid entered the sewer in front of 2134 Chatterton Ave and approximately 15 gallons entered the sewer in front of 2139 Chatterton Ave. The operator immediately realized his error, closed the back hatch and used the vactor's vaccum pump to clean up the spilled liquid off the roadway and pump it back into the truck's cargo tank. The affected area of the street was washed with a detergent and absorbent was applied.  Any remaining liquid on the street's surface was removed and pumped back into the truck's cargo tank using its vacuum tube. NYC Department of Environmental Protection (NYC DEP) was immediately notified about the 40-gallon release to the NYC sewer system. NYC DEP did not take any response action.   The vactor truck was being used to clean an underground electrical structure at this location when a large rock was removed from the structure and became obstructed in the truck's vacuum tube, inhibiting its suction. The mechanic intended to raise the truck's cargo tank in order to troubleshoot and clear the blockage. The levers to raise the cargo tank and open the cargo door are located next to each other in a side control panel. Even though each lever is color coded and clearly labeled indicating the equipment it controls, the mechanic mistakenly pushed the red colored lever that opens the cargo door, instead of pushing the black colored lever that raises the cargo tank body.
column169: The cause of this incident was operator error. The mechanic operated the wrong lever. We have issued a communication bulletin describing this event to be discussed with our operators in order to prevent recurrence.   As part of the incident investigation, we verified that administrative and engineering controls are in place in this truck.  We reviewed the control panel housing the two levers in the truck involved in the incident and we verified that there are instructional posters in the control panel that convey operating instructions in words and in diagrams. Each lever is clearly labeled and color coded indicating the equipment controlled by each lever. The lever which controls the rear hatch has a red handle, the lever that raises and lowers the cargo tank has a black handle. In addition, the control levers have a metal pin interlock that prevents them from being pushed without first removing the pin. A stopper is also present that jams the actuator, similarly stopping the levers from being pushed until the operator moves the stopper away.  To prevent similar incidents, we will verify that all our trucks contain the proper engineering and administrative controls. We will also review our training and procedures to ensure there are clear instructions regarding the raising of the truck's cargo tank to prevent similar spills.  This incident will be communicated to our contractors and other groups performing similar operations.

column168: ACCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AT THIS TIME.  DRIVER IS STILL IN CRITICAL CONDITION AND WE ARE NOT ABLE TO QUESTION HIM FOR HIS ACCOUNT OF THE ACCIDENT.  WHAT WE DO KNOW IS IT APPEARS  DRIVER WAS NOT ABLE TO NEGOTIATE A TURN AND LEFT ROADWAY.  TRUCK AND TRAILER THEN OVERTURNED.  THE ROLL EVEN CAUSED A RUPTURE IN THE VESSEL BODY, RELEASING THE MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT.  IT IS ESTIMATED THE RELEASE WAS IMMEDIATE AND ONLY LASTED A SHORT WHILE AS IT WAS A LARGE RUPTURE AND PRODUCT ESCAPED QUICKLY.  EMERGENCY HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO CRASH SITE.  EXCAVATION EQUIPMENT WAS BROUGHT ON SITE WITHIN 12 HOURS OF CRASH TO MITIGATE SPREAD OF RELEASE.  BERMS WERE PUT IN PLACE, RETENTION PONDS FORMED TO COLLECT LIQUID, AND MELTING SNOW WAS DIVERTED FROM SPILL AREA TO PREVENT FURTHER SPREAD.
column169: AT THIS TIME WE CANNOT PROVIDE AN ANSWER HERE AS THE ACCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AND ROOT CAUSE IS YET TO BE DETERMINED.  SUPPLEMENTAL INFORMATION TO THIS REPORT CAN BE PROVIDED AT A LATER DATE IF NEEDED.

column168: ON 03/10/2015 AT 1630 HOURS CSDT, I WAS ADVISED OF A TANK CAR LEAKING AT THE INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) RAILROAD YARD LOCATED IN BURNHAM, IL. IHB OPERATIONS CENTER ADVISED CAR NUMBER GATX 54345, CONTAINING A FULL ROAD LOAD OF ETHANOLAMINE UN 2491 PG III WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BY AN IHB SWITCHMEN WHILE MOVING THE CAR OUT TO BE SWITCHED. OPERATIONS CENTER AND TRAINMASTER ROB MORRIS PLACED THE YARD ON STANDBY DUE TO THE VAPOR AND CORROSIVENESS OF THE PRODUCT.    UPON ARRIVAL MYSELF AND MATT KETELARR OF SUNPRO SERVICES INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING OUT OF ALL 4 BOTTOM FLANGE BOLTS AT APPROXIMATELY 1 DRIP EVERY 2-3 SECONDS. MATT OF SUNPRO TRIED TIGHTENING THE 4 BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE BOLTS TO NO SUCCESS, THE 4 BOTLS WERE ALREADY AS SECURE AS POSSIBLE. UPON DISCOVERING THE LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED WE PLACED A PRODUCT COMPATIBLE CATCH BASIN UNDERNEATH WHERE THE CAR WAS LEAKING TO CATCH ALL REMAINING DISCHARGE PRODUCT. AFTER THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED THE CAR WAS MOVED SAFELY AND SECURELY TO A BETTER TRACK IN ORDER TO BE OFFLOADED. REMEDIATION OF THE DISCHARGED PRODUCT WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITH SHOVELING UP THE INFECTED BALLAST AND PLACING IT INTO BAGS. THE PRODUCT WAS EVENTUALLY TRANSFERRED ON 3/13/2015 BY SUNPRO TO A SEMI TANK TRUCK AND THE REST OF THE PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER RAIL TANK CAR. THE TANK CAR CAME OUT OF PORT NECHES, TX AND IT IS UNCLEAR HOW LONG THE CAR WAS LEAKING AND HOW MUCH PRODUCT WAS RELEASED THROUGHOUT ITS TRAVELS TO THE IHB. THE RAIL CAR WAS IN ROUTE TO WOLF TERMINALS IN CHICAGO, IL.    ON 3/16/2015 THE CAR WAS CLEANED AND PURGED BY SUNPRO SERVICES. I RECEIVED TO THE CLEAN AND PURGE CERTIFICATE AND ATTACHED IT TO THE TANK CAR.    ON 3/17/2015 THE SHIPPER, HUNTSMAN LLC APPLIED FOR AN OTMA 3 AND THE CAR WAS MOVED TO UNITED RAIL'S GATX FACILITY IN EAST CHICAGO, IN FOR PROPER INSPECTION AND MITIGATION OF WHAT WAS CAUSING THIS CAR TO RELEASE PRODUCT FROM THE 4 BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE BOLTS.
column169: SPOKE WITH IVAN RIVERA OF HUNTSMAN LLC WHO ADVISED THEY WOULD CONTINUE TO USE PROPER PRE SHIPMENT INSPECTIONS IN ORDER TO KEEP SOMETHING LIKE THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column43: FUEL OIL OR HOME HEATING OIL
column168: CTMV WAS PARKED ON A RESIDENTIAL PROPERTY.  THE CMTV OPERATOR WAS STANDING OUTSIDE THE HOME DISPENSING HEATING OIL INTO THE FILL PIPE FOR TWO (PLUMBED TOGETHER) BASEMENT TANKS.  THE HOMEOWNER HAD REMOVED A TWO INCH PLUG ON TOP OF ONE TANK TO INSTALL A LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE.  THE GAUGE WAS NOT SECURED IN THE TANK SO THE TANK OVERFLOWED ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR.  SOME PRODUCT ENETERED A FLOOR DRAIN AND TRAVELED THROUGH DRAINAGE TILE TO A ROADSIDE DITCH.  UPON DISCOVERY THE CTMV WAS TURNED OFF AND VALVES CLOSED. CONTACTS WERE MADE TO MANAGEMENT TO EPA. CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE INITIATED FOR THE BASMENT, TILE, AND ROADSIDE DITCH.
column169: NONE.  HOWEOWNER ERROR BY NOT PROPERLY INSTALLING THE GAUGE IN THE TANK.

column168: INTERSTATE BATTERIES TRUCK WAS ON 9 EAST ON FM 1960 WHEN A VEHICLE TRAVEL WEST CAME ACROSS THE FREEWAY AND HIT THE TRUCK BETWEEN CAB AND REAR CAUSING TRUCK TO ROLLOVER 2 TIMES. THE BATTERIES WERE STACK AND WRAPPED ACCORDING TO DOTS STANDARDS. I'M NOT SURE IF THE TRUCK ROLLING OVER TWICE HAD ANYTHING TO DO WITH PACKING FAILING. I'M SURE IT DIDN'T HELP. HAZ MAT CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS HIRED ONSITE TO ORGANIZE CLEAN UP. TX DOT APPROVED OF CLEAN UP THAT WAS DONE. SOIL SAMPLE  AND WATER SAMPLES FROM DITCH WERE TAKE TO CONFIRM NO HAZ MATERIALS WERE PRESENT.
column169: I DONT BELIEVE THERE WAS ANYTHING DIFFERENT WE COULD HAVE DONE TO PREVENT THIS. I BELIEVE THE WAY IT WAS PACKAGED KEPT IT FROM BEING WORSE.
