column168: PETRO EXPRESS CO. DRIVER WILLIAM GORMAN, WAS TRAVELING SOUTH BOUND ON I 95 IN PRINCE GEORGES COUNTY MD WHEN A MOTORIST DRIVING A FORD FOCUS ENTERED ONTO I 95 FROM EXIT 32. DRIVER OF FORD PROCEEDED TO CROSS SEVERAL LANES ON THE HIGHWAY AND CRASHED INTO A CHEVY MALIBU, ALSO TRAVELING SB 1 95. THE TWO VEHICLES CAME TO AN ABRUPT STOP IN THE MIDDLE OF THE HIGHWAY. PETRO EXPRESS CO. DRIVER TRAVELING BEHIND THE TWO CRASHED VEHICLES ATTEMPTED TO MOVE TO THE RIGHT LANE TO AVOID CRASHING. THE WEIGHT SHIFT OF THE PETROLEUM LOAD CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND CARGO TANK TO OVERTURN. THE PETRO EXPRESS CO. DRIVER MANEUVERED AROUND THE MOTORIST TO ELIMINATE POSSIBLE INJURIES OF THE STOPPED MOTORIST. MSP MD, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT, AND MD SHA RESPONDED, PUMPED OFF THE LOAD FROM TANKER AND REMOVED THE VEHICLE FROM THE ROADWAY.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING ON RT 28 OVER THE BOURNE BRIDGE IN BOURNE MA. AS THE VEHICLE WAS GOING OVER BRIDGE THE TRUCK INEXPLICABLY BEGAN TO ACCELERATE. DRIVER COULD NOT SLOW TRUCK DOWN. THE CAR WENT STRAIGHT THROUGH ROTARY AND FLIPPED OVER. FIRE, POLICE AND HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED. APPROXIMATELY 5000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER. A LICENSED SITE PROFESSIONAL, COSMO GALLINARO, LSP WAS HIRED TO OVERSEE ALL NECESSARY CLEANUP OF SITE.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: Amanda and Pierre were discovered by flight attendants to have on-board Flight NK639 (DTW-TPA) a oxygen cylinder they carried concealed within carry-on baggage.  The discovery was made enroute when a beverage service as being conducted by the flight attendants.    he stated to the flight attendants he carries it as a precaution due to his infant child having lung cancer, sickle cell anemia, and cirrhosis of the liver.  The oxygen cylinder didn't contribute to any event on the aircraft nor was there any release of oxygen reported by the crew.
column169: The concealed oxygen cylinder made it past all checks in place.  Spirit does not permit passengers to transport their own oxygen cylinders.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: Metal container frames rubbed against shrink wrap during breakdown at cargo warehouse and caused powder to leak. Contained in warehouse. Shipment was at final destination and did not travel further.
column169: Care should be made during breakdown for this type of outer packaging.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: The shipment was found leaking in the sort. Upon examination of the interior containers there was no positive closure on the screw on caps, no absorbent material, the barrier bag wasn't closed, nor any dividers to preclude seperation of the inner packagings. Based on the hidden packaging discrepancies I notified FAA HazMat Supervisor Ritchie Verplank in the Chicago (ORD) SECFO. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection.
column169: NO DESCRIPTION INCLUDED.

column168: PROCESSING INCOMING BAGGAGE FROM FLIGHT. BAG ARRIVED ON US AIRWAYS FLIGHT 5506 FROM CHARLOTTE AT 18:55 ON 3/15. BAG WAS SET UP FOR DELIVERY AT BAGGAGE SERVICE OFFICE (BSO) WHEN ODOR WAS NOTED BY EMPLOYEES ANDREA ST. MARTIN AND HOLLY MILLEA. THEY CONTACTED THE PASSENGER HACOTTE PREVILUS, WHO INDICATED THE LIQUID IN THE BAG WAS FOR BEDBUGS. PASSENGER WAS NOT FLUENT IN ENGLISH. EMPLOYEES CONTACTED THE RI AIRPORT POLICE AND WARWICK FIRE DEPARTMENT AS THE LIQUID WAS CAUSING THEIR EYES AND THROATS TO BURN. THEY WERE ADVISED TO EVACUATE THE AREA AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REMOVED BAG FROM THE BSO AND IT WAS TAKEN TO THE GARDEN AREA. THE BAG WAS OPENED AND A SMALL GLASS JAR WITH A STAINED LABEL STATING "CHLORPYRIFOS" WAS REMOVED.
column169: Passenger notification regarding hazardous materials was given to the passenger at time of booking and at check-in.Graphics are also used in the notification to make sure that information is conveyed to non-English speakers.Ms. Previlus checked to indicate she understood the hazardous material restrictions. It'is not known if she did not understand the pesticide was a hazardous material item or was just disregarding the hazardous material notification.

column168: WHILE LOADING TRUCK #9 IN THE YARD, PULLED UP IN FRONT OF THE TANKS TO LOAD CALIFORNIA CARB UNLEADED AND CARB CLEAR DIESEL.  DWAYNE HOOKED UP THE GROUND CABLE TO FRONT BUMPER.  HE TOOK UP THE HOSE AND STARTED TO LOAD UNLEADED.  WHILE UNLEADED, GOT DOWN AND GOT DIESEL HOSE.  WENT BACK UP AND BEGAN LOADING DIESEL INTO ANOTHER COMPARTMENT.    THERE WAS ANOTHER EMPLOYEE ON THE GROUND.  HE WAS GOING TO TURN OFF THE DIESEL PUMP WHEN DWAYNE (WHO WAS ON TOP OF THE TRUCK) LET HIM KNOW.  DWAYNE BENT DOWN AND LOOKED INTO THE COMPARTMENT, ONLY WANTING 200 GALLONS AND IT IS A 500 GALLON COMPARTMENT. AS HE BENT DOWN IT IGNITED THE VAPORS.    DWAYNE HAD SUNGLASSES ON WITH NO GLOVES.  THE IGNITION BALL OF FIRE CAUGHT HIS JACKET ON FIRE.  TODD, THE EMPLOYEE ON THE GROUND, TURNED OFF THE DIESEL PUMP AND THEN WENT  TO THE GAS PUMP AND TURNED IT OFF.  HE THEN DIRECTED DWAYNE TO GET OFF OF THE TRUCK.  DWAYNE JUMPED ONTO THE GROUND.  TODD RAN AROUND THE TRUCK AND ASSISTED IN GETTING THE FLAME OFF OF HIM.  THEN TODD RAN INTO THE OFFICE AND TOLD US TO CALL 911.    LARRY, ANOTHER EMPLOYEE, WHO WAS IN THE OFFICE AT THE TIME, RAN OUTSIDE TO THE TRUCK.  HE CLIMBED TO THE TOP OF THE TRUCK AND THREW BOTH HOSES' ON THE GROUND.  HE THEN CLOSED THE DOMES TO BOTH COMPARTMENTS AND THE FIRE WENT OUT.    THERE IS NO VISUAL EVIDENCE OF THE FIRE ON THE TRUCK.  THE FUEL VAPORS ABOVE IT WERE ON FIRE, NOT THE ACTUAL TRUCK.    THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EMS CAME AND TRANSPORTED DWAYNE TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL.  FROM THERE HE WAS SENT VIA CARE FLIGHT TO UC DAVIS FOR FURTHER TREATMENT.    WHILE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SITE, WE CHECK THE TRUCK AND ALL WAS WELL.  NO SIGNS OF FLAMES.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

column168: Tank car SHLX 273 was in the process of being transferred to another tank car. During the transfer, the manway was opened. A burst of air was sent through the bottom outlet transfer hose, causing bubbles to travel upward through SHLX 273, releasing approximately fifteen gallons of product through the open manway.  Molten sulfur splashed on top and down the sides of the car and onto a contractor employee engaged in transfer operations below the manway.  He received some scalding on the neck and arm and was transported to an urgent care facility where he was assessed.
column169: No additional comments.
